text: Suspected Unapproved Parts and Counterfeit Parts 1 Suspected Unapproved Parts and Counterfeit Parts SUP Program Office Overview To help guard against use of unapproved parts, the FAA created a special SUPs program in 1995. A special SUPs office, located in the Washington, DC area, coordinates the FAA’s efforts to identify, investigate and ultimately remove any such parts from spares stocks, or occasionally, from aircraft themselves. In July 2007 the responsible organization for the SUPs program

was realigned from FAA’s Flight Standards Service (AFS) to the Aircraft Certification Service (AIR). The FAA employs a national reporting system (FAA Hotline Program) to receive reports of potential unapproved parts entering the aviation system primarily at the supply and repair level of aircraft maintenance. The SUP program, administered by AIR and AFS, employs surveillance, investigation, community wide notification, and where warranted, enforcement actions to address the problem of unapproved

parts in the aviation system. The most important goals of a SUPs investigation are to trace suspect parts to their source, determine whether they pose a threat to aviation safety, and if so, take corrective action and remove them from the system. FAA investigators gather photographic evidence, copies of records and witness statements. Parts given to the inspector during the course of an investigation are officially cataloged. Investigators write detailed narratives to document the scope of the

investigation and their findings. If criminal activity is suspected, the FAA coordinates its investigation with the appropriate law enforcement authorities. If the investigation determines a part is truly unapproved, the following actions must take place. The unapproved parts must be accounted for or the potential end users must be notified. If end users cannot be notified directly, then the FAA sends out an Unapproved Parts Notification (UPN) alerting the aviation community to the problem. UPNs

advise that the parts be deactivated or removed, depending on the type of aircraft. Suspected Unapproved Parts and Counterfeit Parts 2 Summary of SUPs, Unapproved Parts and Counterfeit Parts Suspected Unapproved Part or SUP A SUP is a part that is suspected of failing to meet any of the criteria of 14 CFR 21.8 or 21.9 for FAA-approved production, or a part that for any reason, a person believes is not approved for use on a TC product. Reasons for suspecting a part is unapproved may include: •

Differences in finish, size, or color; • Improper (or lack of) identification; • Incomplete or altered paperwork; or • Any other unusual or abnormal characteristic. Note 1: An approved part used in the wrong application must be addressed as a potential 14 CFR 43 maintenance violation. It should not be reported as a SUP. Note 2: In this particular case the term “part” does not include raw materials, (such as sheet metal stock, sealants, lubricants, raw forgings, castings, or billet material or

similar). FAA-Approved A part is considered FAA-Approved if it is manufactured and conforms to a type design in accordance with 14 CFR 21. The following are examples of approved parts: • Parts produced under a type or production certificate; • Parts manufactured under a Parts Manufacturing Approval (PMA); • Parts produced by an owner or operator for maintaining or altering his own product; • Parts produced under an FAA Technical Standard Order (TSO); and • Standard parts (such as bolts and nuts)

that conform to established industry or U.S. specifications. Unapproved Part An unapproved part is a part that fails to meet any of the criteria pursuant to 14 CFR 21.8 or 21.9. This definition also includes parts that have been intentionally misrepresented, including counterfeit parts. Examples include: • Supplier produced parts for an approved manufacturer directly shipped to end users without the Production Approval Holder’s (PAH) authorization or a separate Parts manufacturer Approval (PMA);

• Parts that have passed through a PAH’s quality system which do not conform to the approved design/data; Suspected Unapproved Parts and Counterfeit Parts 3 • Counterfeit parts - parts offered as having been produced under an FAA production approval, where no such FAA approval was issued; • Parts for which required documentation cannot be provided; • Life limited parts misrepresented as new or having useful time left. If a part is determined to be repairable, it should be documented and

controlled so that it is not returned to aviation service until it meets all the necessary airworthy requirements. If the owner determines that a part is not repairable, it should be scrapped in such a manner that it cannot be returned to aviation service. If a salvaged part is received, proper documentation and examination is crucial to determining if it is eligible for installation on TC products; • Parts previously installed on, or manufactured for, military aircraft that have not been shown

to conform to type design criteria pursuant to FAA regulations; • Surplus parts (left-overs or production over-runs) produced by a company not possessing a PMA or direct ship authority, that were manufactured to satisfy a contract or purchase order with a PAH and were never accepted into the PAH approved quality system. Counterfeit Part A counterfeit part is type of “unapproved part” made or altered to imitate or resemble an approved item without authority or right, and with the intent to

mislead or defraud by passing the imitation as original or genuine. Counterfeit parts may be newly manufactured or appear to be serviceable; however, they are deliberately misrepresented as being produced to an FAA-approved design or other acceptable method. Detecting Counterfeit Parts • The most common method of a counterfeiter is re-marking of parts, which include: ᴼ Marking with a newer date code; ᴼ Changing the parts revision to a higher or current level; ᴼ Changing the manufacturer or

country of origin of parts to be more marketable; ᴼ Similar but unequal parts to a different device type. • Another common method is reclaiming used parts from the Electronic-waste stream and presenting them as unused; • Packaging surplus or rejected wafers or dice as if they were good parts from the original manufacturer; • Reverse-engineering and manufacturing in low-cost facilities, marking and selling them as the legal Original Equipment Manufacturers parts; • Sale of non-functional

components; • Providing false traceability for all the above. Suspected Unapproved Parts and Counterfeit Parts 4 Impact of Counterfeiting Whether the parts are electronic, mechanical or other, these all adversely affect the U.S. and international supply chain. Possible effects may include: For government: • National security or civilian safety issues; • Costs of enforcement; • Lost tax revenue due to illegal sales of counterfeit parts. For industry: • Costs to mitigate this risk; • Costs to

replace failed parts; • Lost sales; • Lost brand value or damage to business image. For consumers: • Costs when products fail due to lower quality and reliability of counterfeit parts; • Potential safety concerns. Reasons Behind Counterfeit Parts Existence The most common motivational factors for why counterfeit parts exist are: • Profit is the primary incentive for counterfeiting. However, there are unique conditions that make aerospace and defense products susceptible to counterfeiting,

including a long-life cycle and diminishing manufacturing sources and material shortages; • Supporting aerospace and defense products throughout their lifecycle sometimes requires the use of parts that may no longer be available from the Original Equipment Manufacturer (OEM), authorized aftermarket manufacturer or through franchised or authorized distributors or resellers; • Source material is cheap – production scrap, reclaimed salvage (“E-Waste”), obsolete revisions, or out-of-date for use; •

High product demand is created by: ᴼ Out of stock (high short-term demand or lack of availability); ᴼ Out of production (obsolescence); ᴼ Manufacturer-limited (poor yields, allocation to select customers); ᴼ Restrictions on country of origin; and ᴼ Pressure to reduce costs; • Ready sources of low-cost labor and lack of legal and environmental oversight countries include: China, Taiwan, Malaysia, and Singapore; • Under-utilized and low-cost manufacturing facilities in developing countries focus

on wafer fabs, device packaging lines, and similar; Suspected Unapproved Parts and Counterfeit Parts 5 • Ability to steal, buy, or reverse-engineer designs for high-value components. • Low risk due to poor record of detection or identification. Detection of SUPs Supplier Evaluation FAA regulation 14 CFR 21, Certification Procedures for Products and Articles, requires that a production approval holder’s quality system provide a means of determining that supplier-produced components such as

materials, parts, and subassemblies, or services such as processes, calibration and similar conform to FAA-approved design data. The process should include criteria for the initial evaluation, selection, periodic or ongoing evaluations, and disapproval of suppliers. The FAA encourages PAHs to conduct an initial and periodic onsite evaluation based on risk factors. Guidance on this function may be found in Advisory Circular (AC) 21-43. Although onsite supplier evaluations are not required for

repair stations and non-PAH holder facilities, repair stations are required to ensure each person maintaining or altering, or performing preventive maintenance, shall perform the work in such a manner and use materials of such a quality, that the condition of the aircraft, airframe, aircraft engine, propeller, or appliance worked on will be at least equal to its original or properly altered condition. To ensure that only aviation quality materials are used in the repair of parts and components

these facilities may elect to follow the guidance provided in AC 20-154, Guide for Developing a Receiving Inspection System for Aircraft Parts and Material and AC 20-62 Eligibility, Quality, and Identification of Aeronautical Replacement Parts, to help prevent introduction of unairworthy parts into inventory. Procurement A procedure is established to ensure the procurement of approved parts prior to purchasing parts and material for installation in type certificated (TC) products. This procedure

should include the following at a minimum: • Methods of identifying distributors and/or suppliers who have a documentation system and receiving inspection system that ensures the traceability of their parts to an FAA-approved source; • Methods of screening unfamiliar distributors and/or suppliers to determine if the parts present a potential risk of being unapproved. The following situations may raise questions: ᴼ A quoted price that is significantly lower than the price quoted by other

distributors and/or suppliers of the same part; ᴼ A delivery schedule that is significantly shorter than that of other distributors and/or suppliers (when the stock of a like item is exhausted); Suspected Unapproved Parts and Counterfeit Parts 6 ᴼ Sales quotes or discussions from unidentified distributors that imply an unlimited supply of parts, components, or materials are available to the end user; or ᴼ A distributor or supplier’s inability to provide substantiating documentation that the part

was produced in accordance with an FAA approval or inspected, repaired, overhauled, rebuilt preserved, or altered, pursuant to 14 CFR 43 Maintenance, Preventive Maintenance, Rebuilding, and Alteration. • Traceability to approved design and production approval should be requested by purchasers on their purchase orders for all parts intended for use on TC products. In order to establish appropriate traceability, documentation requirements for a particular category of parts, please refer to the

“Documentation Matrix” in Appendix 1 of FAA AC 00-56. Receiving Inspection Internal procedures should include a means of identifying unapproved parts and preventing their acceptance. An effective receiving inspection should address the following suggested areas: • Confirm that the packaging of the part identifies the supplier or distributor and is free from alteration or damage; • Verify that the actual part and delivery receipt reflect the same information as the purchase order regarding part

and serial number; • Verify that the identification on the part has not been tampered with. For example, serial number stamped over, label or part/serial numbers improper or missing, vibro-etch or serial numbers located at other than the normal location; • Ensure that the parts’ shelf life and/or life limit has not expired, if applicable; • Conduct a visual inspection of the part and supporting documents to the extent necessary to determine if the part is traceable to an FAA-approved source. For

detailed guidelines on the identification of replacement parts refer to AC 20-62. • Conduct random sampling of standard hardware packaged in large quantities in a manner that corresponds to the type and quantity of the parts; • Segregate suspect parts and attempt to resolve any issues regarding the part’s questionable status through your supplier prior to initiating a SUP report. For guidelines on how to set up a receiving inspection system, refer to AC 20-154. Disposition of SUPs and

Counterfeit Parts Proper disposition of suspected unapproved parts or counterfeit parts prevents their reintroduction into the supply chain. If a part is returned to the supplier, whether an authorized distributor, OEM, or independent broker, it is subject to resale to meet market needs. Resale of returned product has the potential to reintroduce known or Suspected Unapproved Parts and Counterfeit Parts 7 suspected counterfeit parts into the supply chain. Returning counterfeit parts to the

supplier allows counterfeiters to learn that their attempts were detected. In civil aviation, 14 CFR 43.10 governs the disposition of life-limited aircraft parts. The FAA has issued Advisory Circular 21-43 Appendix D as guidance for dispositioning of scrap products and articles and instructions for mutilation. Effective mutilation may be accomplished by one or a combination of the following methods: grinding, burning, removal of a major integral feature, permanent distortion of products and

articles, cutting a significant size hole with a cutting torch or saw, melting, sawing into many small pieces, and removing manufacturer identification, part, lot, batch, and serial number. If a part has been reported in an Unapproved Parts Notification or UPN, potential consumers are advised to quarantine the product to prevent installation. A determination will be made regarding their eligibility for installation, removed and replaced to prevent failure during installation, or returned to the

company for disposition. As part of the UPN, the FAA has a section in which they ask for “any information on the discovery of the above referenced parts from any source, the means used to identify the source, and the actions taken to remove them from the aircraft and/or parts inventories. Holders of a UPN may not have a contractual right to scrap or mutilate a part; repair stations may not own the part that they work on. Additional Recommendations: • Companies should develop their internal

disposition plan with the assistance of their procurement, legal, and quality personnel; • The disposition plan should also address supplier payment conditions when counterfeit material is discovered. Reporting Procedure It is the FAA’s policy to encourage the disclosure of information regarding aviation safety. Reporters may be concerned with the potential repercussions of reporting the discovery of parts that are alleged to be unapproved. Although reports may be submitted anonymously,

requesting the reporter’s name enables the FAA to verify information and provide confirmation and/or follow up to the reporter. FAA Form 8120-11 includes instructions to complete the form, and provides the information needed to initiate a SUP investigation. If you complete the form online, it may be submitted electronically to the FAA Hotline. You may also send a completed form to the FAA Hotline Office via e-mail at FAAHotline@faa.gov, or you can mail it in accordance with the instructions
listed in AC 21-29.
